 a gruesome place, kakoy zhutkiy dom,” she said, sitting on the chair near the telephone and taking off her galoshes—such familiar movements! “Look at that aquarelle with the minarets. They must be terrible people.”

“No,” said Pnin, “they are my friends.”

“My dear Timofey,” she said, as he escorted her upstairs, “you have had some pretty awful friends in your time.”

“And here is my room,” said Pnin.

